22/02/2021 17:24 - Amorzinho: Despite SLR relevance in SE area some critical issues, drawbacks, challenges, and lessons learned regarding SLR were presented over the past decade, such as (Kuhrmann et al, 2017): (i) Lack of reflections on the use of SLR outcomes; (ii) Lack of connection with industry; (iii) Many SLRs in SE do not present neither a strong synthesis and a deep discussion nor their applicability in academia and industry; (iv) Many time and effort are needed to conduct/update SLR; (v) Not-enough SLR documentation are provided; (vi) The most SLR do not be updated, causing results outdated, but SLR should be regularly updated to preserve their value to be used by the SE community (i.e., industry). Even that researchers focused on solving technical issues of SLRs, such as tools and new techniques to better plan, conduct, and report SLRs, these are still open issues.

[16:36, 23/08/2021] Vinicius dos Santos: My major concern with this paper relates to the difference between a systematic mapping study (SMS) and a systematic literature review (SLR). To my knowledge, many literature reviews, especially a few years ago, are technically (methodologically and reporting wise) SMS, but are reported as SLRs in the SE discipline. An SLR and SMS have slightly different objectives, and thus, focus on different categories of literature to form their solutions. For example, an SLR ideally should focus only on empirical literature. Reporting an SMS as SLR could also lead to one of the problems, i.e., lack of an effect on the industry. For example, whether to use method X or Y is more relevant/useful for the industry rather than what does the literature, in general, say about b‚Ä¶
